{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Optional authentication for the rebar MCP server (OAuth 2.1 Resource-Server model)\n\n## Context\n\n`rebar-mcp` (`src/rebar/mcp_server.py`, `mcp.server.fastmcp.FastMCP(\"rebar\")`) is today\n**stdio-only**: `build_server().run()` is called with no transport argument. It has **no HTTP\ntransport and no per-request/session plumbing**. Per the MCP authorization spec, authentication is\nan **HTTP-transport concern** ŌĆö stdio servers *should not* authenticate (credentials come from the\nenvironment). rebar has deliberately kept MCP stdio-only and met every remote need with separate\nFastAPI library-mode services (the Gerrit `review_bot`, the in-flight op-cert service), so\n**nothing consumes rebar-mcp over the network today** (Gerrit and GitHub Actions use the rebar\nlibrary/CLI in-process, per ADR-0007).\n\nThis epic adds an **optional** capability: rebar-mcp can serve over HTTP and require\nauthentication, acting as an **OAuth 2.1 Resource Server** that validates inbound bearer tokens and\nadvertises RFC 9728 Protected Resource Metadata. The capability is generic (provider-agnostic) so\nany organization can front it with its own identity provider ŌĆö it is **not** coupled to this\nproject's dev auth model. Design-of-record: session log `emanatory-confounded-dodo` plus the\nhigher-effort coherence/peer/security review pass captured in the same log.\n\n## Why (beneficiary + problem)\n\n**Beneficiary:** an operator/organization (including rebar itself, as future follow-on) that wants\nto expose rebar MCP tools to remote MCP clients (Claude Code / an IDE / a CI job) over the network\ninstead of a local stdio subprocess. **Problem today:** there is no HTTP transport and no\nauthentication, so a shared/hosted rebar store cannot be reached by a remote MCP client without\nexposing it unauthenticated. This epic makes a remote rebar-mcp endpoint possible and safe to\nrequire auth on, verified locally.\n\n## Approach & rationale (positive)\n\nBuild rebar's **own** token verifiers against the **official `mcp` SDK's `TokenVerifier` seam**\n(`mcp.server.auth.provider.TokenVerifier.verify_token(token) -> AccessToken | None`), wired via\n`FastMCP(token_verifier=ŌĆ”, auth=AuthSettings(ŌĆ”))`, and serve the optional Streamable-HTTP transport\nthe SDK already provides. rebar is a **Resource Server only** ŌĆö it validates tokens and advertises\ndiscovery metadata; it is **not** an Authorization Server and does **not** implement Dynamic Client\nRegistration (identity is delegated to the deploying org's IdP).\n\n**Why this fits:** (a) the official SDK ŌĆö already a dependency ŌĆö provides the `TokenVerifier` seam,\n`AuthSettings`, RFC 9728 metadata routes, `TransportSecuritySettings`, and Streamable-HTTP transport\nnatively; the verifiers are small modules on a stable, blessed seam. (b) It is the mainstream\nself-hosted path (GitHub, Grafana, Neon, GitLab, and the SDK's own `simple-auth` example build auth\non the official SDK; GitHub's remote server likewise delegates identity and does not do DCR). (c) It\navoids the standalone `fastmcp` framework, whose `server.auth` module is semver-exempt and has had\nmultiple CVEs. (d) It keeps every line under rebar's own tests/CI/version control.\n\n**RS-only + no-DCR is defensible, not a usability gap.** Claude Code / Claude.ai do not *require*\nDCR: they auto-discover via the RFC 9728 PRM rebar serves (pointing at the org IdP), and when the\nIdP lacks anonymous DCR (Entra, Cognito, default Keycloak/Auth0/Okta) the user falls back to\nfirst-class **manual `--client-id`/`--client-secret`** or a **static bearer `--header`** ŌĆö both of\nwhich rebar's PRM + static verifier serve directly. S7 documents these three connection paths.\n\n## Security (this epic crosses a trust boundary ŌĆö the core of the plan)\n\nEnabling HTTP exposes rebar-mcp to **lower-trust network actors**. The posture is first-class and\npropagated to every child:\n\n- **Authentication is the deliverable.** With auth enabled, every request is admitted only on a\n  validated bearer token; an unauthenticated request receives **401 + `WWW-Authenticate`** with the\n  RFC 9728 `resource_metadata` URL. Identity is delegated to the org IdP; rebar mints no tokens.\n- **The composite verifier is the single audience/fail-closed choke point.** The SDK does **not**\n  validate token audience and `AccessToken.resource` defaults to `None`, so there is no SDK\n  backstop. Therefore the **composite** re-validates every returned token: it rejects unless\n  `AccessToken.resource` is present **and** equals the single configured `auth_resource_server_url`\n  (RFC 8707). Every verifier ŌĆö including static and trusted-proxy, which have no natural token\n  audience ŌĆö must populate `.resource` explicitly. A verifier cannot bypass the audience check.\n- **One resource, one audience.** There is a single `auth_resource_server_url`; it is what the PRM\n  advertises AND the audience every verifier validates against ŌĆö they are never independent.\n- **Fail-closed everywhere:** any verifier that raises is logged and treated as **non-acceptance**\n  (never acceptance); if no verifier returns a valid, audience-matching token the request is denied\n  (401). Misconfigured auth, an unknown `auth_strategies` entry, `auth_enabled=true` with an empty\n  composite, or auth-enabled-over-HTTP with no verifier wired all **refuse to start**. An HTTP\n  transport with auth disabled refuses to start unless `REBAR_MCP_ALLOW_UNAUTHENTICATED_HTTP` is set.\n- **Transport hardening:** DNS-rebinding/`Origin` protection on by default with explicit loopback\n  defaults; loopback bind by default; a non-loopback bind requires explicit host/origin allowlists\n  AND an explicit TLS-at-edge acknowledgment (bearer tokens/secrets must never cross the network in\n  cleartext). Discovery URLs derive from the configured `auth_resource_server_url` (validated https\n  for non-loopback), not the request scheme ŌĆö the behind-a-proxy correctness fix.\n- **No token passthrough** to any upstream (confused-deputy prohibition); tokens/secrets never\n  logged (a redaction layer is required and tested).\n- **Authenticated ŌēĀ authorized (named residual).** Any authenticated principal wields rebar's full\n  ambient authority (writes auto-push; `reconcile live` uses rebar's own git/Jira creds) gated only\n  by server-level `required_scopes` and the existing `REBAR_MCP_READONLY`/`ALLOW_JIRA_SYNC`/\n  `ALLOW_LLM` env gates ŌĆö which now also gate remote actors. Per-tool scopeŌåÆcapability authorization\n  is deferred and documented as a residual risk. Rate-limiting/brute-force protection is delegated\n  to the edge proxy in v1, with mandated high-entropy static tokens; documented as a residual.\n\n## Scope\n\n**In scope:** an optional Streamable-HTTP transport; a provider-agnostic auth framework (composite\n`TokenVerifier` that is the single audience/fail-closed choke point + config-driven selection)\nshipping five verifiers (static bearer, JWKS/JWT, RFC 7662 introspection, trusted-proxy passthrough,\npluggable custom); RFC 9728 metadata + 401; the security/transport hardening above; local\nverification (pytest); docs + an ADR; config/manifest updates (`McpConfig`, `MCP_ENV_VARS`,\n`server.json`, regenerated `mcp-reference.md`/`env-vars.md`).\n\n**Out of scope (explicit):** deploying an authenticated endpoint on AWS / `rebar.solutions.navateam.com`\nand any Gerrit/CI reconfiguration (Gerrit and CI do not use MCP ŌĆö deliberate follow-on); rebar\nacting as an Authorization Server / DCR / token issuance; per-tool scopeŌåÆcapability authorization\n(server-level `required_scopes` only); rate-limiting inside rebar (edge-proxy responsibility in v1);\nGitHub-**user** and Gerrit authentication (neither is an OAuth token issuer ŌĆö only a deploying org's\nproxy/custom concern). stdio remains the default transport and is unchanged.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- A rebar-mcp operator can run the server over HTTP with authentication **required**, using any of\n  the five shipped verifier modes, configured entirely through the existing flat `[mcp]` config/env\n  surface ŌĆö with stdio still the default and auth off by default.\n- The trust-boundary guarantees hold and are demonstrated locally: unauthenticated ŌåÆ 401 +\n  `WWW-Authenticate` + served PRM; valid token ŌåÆ 200; insufficient scope ŌåÆ 403; a token whose\n  `resource` is absent or ŌēĀ `auth_resource_server_url` is rejected at the composite regardless of\n  which verifier produced it; a disallowed `Host`/`Origin` ŌåÆ 421/403.\n- Misconfiguration and downgrade are fail-closed: unknown strategy, empty composite with auth on,\n  auth-enabled-HTTP with no verifier, or unauthenticated HTTP without the explicit ack all refuse to\n  start; non-loopback bind requires allowlists + the TLS-at-edge ack.\n- A third-party operator can connect an interactive Claude client (documented paths) and the design\n  is provider-agnostic (no rebar-specific IdP assumptions).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] All child stories (S1ŌĆōS7) are closed.\n- [ ] `rebar-mcp` serves over an optional Streamable-HTTP transport while stdio remains the default\n      and default behavior is byte-unchanged when the new flat `mcp.*` keys are unset (observable:\n      the existing `tests/interfaces/facades/test_mcp.py` stdio suite still passes).\n- [ ] With auth enabled, the local suite demonstrates 401-without-token (with a `WWW-Authenticate`\n      header carrying the RFC 9728 `resource_metadata` URL), a served PRM document, 200-with-valid-\n      token, 403-insufficient-scope, and rejection of a token whose `resource` ŌēĀ `auth_resource_server_url`\n      enforced at the composite.\n- [ ] All five verifier modes (static, JWKS/JWT, introspection, trusted-proxy, custom) are\n      selectable via the flat `mcp.auth_strategies` list / `REBAR_MCP_*` env vars, each has passing\n      tests, and each populates `AccessToken.resource` so the composite audience check applies.\n- [ ] Fail-closed startup is tested: unknown `auth_strategies` entry, `auth_enabled` with an empty\n      composite, auth-enabled HTTP with no verifier wired, and HTTP with auth disabled and no\n      `REBAR_MCP_ALLOW_UNAUTHENTICATED_HTTP` all refuse to start.\n- [ ] New flat config keys and env vars are reflected in `MCP_ENV_VARS` and `server.json` (the CI\n      manifest drift gate `scripts/check_server_manifest.py` passes) and in regenerated\n      `docs/mcp-reference.md` / `docs/env-vars.md`.\n- [ ] `docs/mcp-auth.md` and an ADR document the resource-server-only model, the composite audience\n      choke point, the five verifier modes, the security posture (incl. the authenticatedŌēĀauthorized\n      residual and rate-limiting delegation), the behind-a-proxy deployment (TLS + allowlists +\n      discovery URLs), and the three interactive-client connection paths.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass on the final integrated branch.\n\n## Testing strategy (children carry the tiers/oracles)\n\nVerification is entirely local (no AWS). Each verifier is unit-tested against its own real logic\n(valid/invalid/audience/expiry/algorithm-confusion/rotation/fail-closed/header-spoofing cases), and\nthe HTTP+auth surface is integration-tested by driving the SDK's Streamable-HTTP ASGI entrypoint\nwith an in-process `httpx` `ASGITransport` client (asserting HTTP status, the `WWW-Authenticate`\nheader, and the served PRM document). Each child story names its test tier and observable oracle.\n\n## Compatibility & rollback\n\nPurely **additive**: stdio stays the default, auth is off by default, all new behavior is gated\nbehind new, unset-by-default flat `mcp.*` keys, so existing stdio deployments and the existing MCP\ntests are unaffected. The dependency changes are pinning `mcp>=1.28.1,<2` (the v2-alpha renames the\nSDK surface; 1.28.1 is at/above the DNS-rebinding fix) and adding `pyjwt[crypto]` for the JWKS\nverifier. Rollback is config-level: leave the new keys unset (or `mcp.transport=stdio`) for exactly\ntoday's behavior."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784068913314822001,"uuid":"6dd52971-61fc-4632-b26c-2120c064c3c0"}